h3. Summary

Using the REST api to update an issue field (eg. fixVersions) with specifically incorrect JSON will return successful (204 No Content), and wipe the field instead of returning an error.

h3. Steps to Reproduce

# Send a PUT request to /rest/api2/issue/<issueno> with the following payload:

{code}
{ "fields": { "fixVersions": [ { "add": "1.2.3" } ] } }
{code}

h3. Expected Results

JIRA should return an error, indicating that the JSON is incorrect. In this case, the JSON does not have the correct key to identify the type of version we are trying to add (eg. name, id, etc).

h3. Actual Results

JIRA will wipe the fixVersions field, and return HTTP 204 (No Content, ie. Success).

h3. Notes
Correct JSON for the same update would look like:

{code}
{ "fields": { "fixVersions": [ { "name": "1.2.3" } ] } }
OR
{ "update": { "fixVersions": [ { "add": { "name": "1.2.3" } } ] } }
{code}
